const PHASE_API = {
  name:"Phase 3 · API Design",id:"api",icon:"🔌",phase:"API Layer",color:"#2563eb",
  sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
  short:"Protocol, gateway, versioning, rate limiting — your API is the contract you'll live with the longest",
  detail:{
    what:"The API layer is the contract surface between your system and everything that consumes it: web and mobile clients, partner integrations, third-party developers, internal services, and even future systems you haven't imagined yet. It encompasses four critical decisions that compound over time. (1) Wire protocol: REST (HTTP+JSON — universally understood, tooling everywhere), GraphQL (HTTP+JSON with a query language — clients request exactly the shape of data they need in a single round trip), gRPC (HTTP/2+Protobuf — binary, fast, code-generated clients with type safety), or WebSocket (persistent bidirectional connection for real-time push). Most mature systems use a mix: REST or GraphQL for external clients, gRPC for internal service-to-service, WebSocket for live features. (2) Gateway/edge layer: the single front door that handles cross-cutting concerns — authentication, rate limiting, SSL termination, request routing, logging, request transformation — so that each downstream service doesn't have to reimplement them. (3) Versioning strategy: how you evolve the API over time without breaking existing consumers. This is the decision you'll regret most if you skip it. (4) Contract style: naming conventions, pagination approach, error format, filtering/sorting patterns, and idempotency behavior that make the API predictable and self-consistent. Together, these four dimensions determine how easy your system is to integrate with, how resilient it is to change, and how much technical debt accumulates in your client applications. A well-designed API is a force multiplier — every team that integrates with it moves faster. A poorly designed one is a tax on every consumer, forever.",
    why:"API decisions are uniquely sticky — stickier than database choices, stickier than language choices, stickier than architecture choices. Why? Because a public API has external consumers you cannot control. Once a mobile app with your v1 API is in the App Store, 20–30% of users will still be running that app version 6+ months later. Partner integrations are even stickier — a B2B customer who spent 3 months integrating your API into their ERP system will not happily re-integrate when you ship breaking changes. Third-party developers who built businesses on your API (think Twitter's early ecosystem) will revolt or die. This means a v1 mistake might live for 5–10 years. Getting the protocol right (do we need GraphQL's flexibility or is REST sufficient?), the versioning right (URL path vs header vs query param — each has different caching and routing implications), and the contract style right (consistent error codes, pagination, idempotency) at the start saves enormous pain later. Get it wrong and you face a brutal choice: break consumers (losing trust, partners, and revenue) or maintain old API versions alongside new ones indefinitely (paying double the testing, documentation, and maintenance cost). The most successful APIs in the industry — Stripe, Twilio, GitHub — all share one trait: their designers spent disproportionate time on API design relative to implementation, because they understood that the API surface is the product for developers. Stripe's API is so well-designed that it's frequently cited as the reason companies choose Stripe over competitors, even when competitors offer lower fees. That's the compound interest of good API design.",
    numbers:"Plan for versioning from day 1, even if you only have v1 — the cost of adding versioning retroactively is 10× higher than building it in. Breaking change policy benchmarks: public APIs typically offer a 6–12 month deprecation window (Stripe gives 2+ years of backward compatibility); B2B APIs may need 12–24 months due to enterprise change management cycles; internal APIs can break with 2–4 weeks notice if you control all consumers. Latency budget: an API gateway adds 1–5ms per request (managed gateways like AWS API Gateway sit at the higher end; tuned Envoy proxies at the lower end) — account for this in your end-to-end latency SLO. Mobile app version distribution: analytics consistently show 20–30% of users are on app versions >6 months old, and 5–10% are on versions >1 year old. Design APIs assuming you cannot force client upgrades. Idempotency dedup windows: 24–48 hours is standard (Stripe uses 24h); shorter risks legitimate retries being rejected, longer wastes storage tracking used keys. Pagination: cursor-based pagination is O(1) per page regardless of offset depth; offset-based is O(N) and breaks on moving datasets (new items shift offsets). Always use cursors for any list that changes."
  },
  tradeoffs:[
    {axis:"Developer experience vs Performance",left:"GraphQL: clients request exactly what they need, self-documenting schema, excellent tooling (Apollo Studio, GraphiQL) — but server-side complexity and potential for expensive queries",right:"gRPC: binary Protobuf is 5–10× smaller, HTTP/2 multiplexing reduces connection overhead, code-generated clients ensure type safety — but harder to debug (binary), poor browser/CDN support",pos:0.5},
    {axis:"Simplicity vs Flexibility",left:"REST: universally understood, trivial to debug with curl, every tool/proxy/CDN supports it, enormous ecosystem — but over-fetching (getting 50 fields when you need 3) and under-fetching (needing 4 round trips for one screen) are real problems",right:"GraphQL: clients compose exactly the query they need, one round trip for complex data needs — but you've given clients a query language against your backend, which requires depth limiting, complexity analysis, and careful authorization",pos:0.5},
    {axis:"Stability vs Evolvability",left:"Strict versioning (/v1/, /v2/) with long deprecation windows — clients are never surprised by changes, but you maintain multiple versions simultaneously",right:"Evolutionary design (additive-only changes, no versions) — simpler to maintain, but requires extreme discipline to never break backward compatibility, and eventually the accumulated 'additive cruft' makes the API confusing",pos:0.5},
    {axis:"Contract-first vs Code-first",left:"Contract-first (write OpenAPI/Protobuf spec, generate code): ensures the API is thoughtfully designed before implementation, enables parallel frontend/backend development, catches breaking changes in CI — but requires spec tooling discipline",right:"Code-first (write handlers, generate spec): faster to prototype, API emerges naturally from implementation — but often results in leaky abstractions that expose internal structure, and the generated spec is descriptive not prescriptive",pos:0.4}
  ],
  pitfalls:[
    {name:"No versioning strategy — the most common and most expensive API mistake",desc:"You ship v1 of your API. Six months later, you realize the response shape for /users is wrong — you need to nest the address fields inside an 'address' object instead of having them flat. Every mobile app and partner integration in the wild is parsing the flat format. You now face a terrible choice: (1) break all existing clients instantly (losing trust, causing outages for your consumers), (2) maintain both shapes forever in the same endpoint with content negotiation (complex, error-prone), or (3) hastily invent a versioning scheme under pressure (inconsistent, poorly thought through). The fix is trivial if done on day 1: include the version in the URL path (/v1/users — simplest, works with all CDNs and proxies) or in a request header (Accept: application/vnd.myapi.v1+json — more RESTful, but harder to test in a browser). Stripe's approach is the gold standard: version by date in a header (Stripe-Version: 2024-06-20), with every account pinned to the API version that existed when they signed up, and explicit opt-in to upgrade. This means old integrations never break, but new ones get the latest design."},
    {name:"Leaky abstractions — your database schema leaking through the API",desc:"Your API returns { 'usr_nm': 'Alice', 'crt_dt': '2024-01-15', 'fk_org_id': 42 } — those are your database column names, complete with abbreviations and foreign key prefixes. Now you want to rename usr_nm to full_name in the DB. You can't, because every client is parsing 'usr_nm.' The API should be a deliberate, designed contract — human-readable field names (user_name, created_at, organization_id), intentional structure (nested objects where they make sense), and explicit about what's included (don't dump every column — only fields the client needs). Think of the API as a UI for developers: it should be intuitive, consistent, and decoupled from your internal implementation. Use a mapping/serialization layer (serializers in Rails, Pydantic models in FastAPI, DTOs in Java) that translates between internal representation and API representation."},
    {name:"Pagination as an afterthought — works at 100, explodes at 100K",desc:"GET /users returns all users in a single response. At 100 users, it's 10KB and fast. At 100,000 users, it's 100MB, takes 30 seconds to serialize, and OOMs your client's mobile app. Even worse: GET /users?page=500&per_page=20 uses offset pagination, which requires the database to scan and skip 10,000 rows before returning 20. At page 5000, the DB is scanning 100,000 rows per request. And if a new user is added between page requests, items shift — the client sees duplicates or misses entries. The correct approach: cursor-based pagination from day 1 on every list endpoint, even if you have 10 records. Return a 'next_cursor' token (typically an encoded ID or timestamp) that the client passes to get the next page. Cursor-based pagination is O(1) per page (the DB uses an index seek, not a scan), handles moving datasets correctly (no duplicates or misses), and scales to billions of records. Libraries: graphql-relay (for GraphQL connections pattern), django-rest-framework cursor pagination, Stripe's auto_pagination in their SDKs."},
    {name:"No request idempotency — the double-charge disaster",desc:"A mobile client on a flaky 3G connection sends POST /charges with a $50 charge. The server processes it and sends the response, but the response is lost in transit. The client, not having received a response, retries the same request. The server processes it again — the customer is charged $100 instead of $50. This happens in production, at scale, regularly. The solution: idempotency keys. The client generates a unique key (UUID) and sends it in the Idempotency-Key header with every mutating request. The server checks if it's seen this key before: if yes, return the cached response without re-executing; if no, execute and cache the response. Dedup window is typically 24 hours. This is not optional for any API that handles money, creates resources, or triggers side effects. Stripe popularized this pattern and requires idempotency keys on every POST endpoint. Implementation: store (idempotency_key, response_status, response_body, created_at) in Redis or your DB with a 24h TTL. Check on every mutating request before processing."},
    {name:"Errors with no machine-readable code — the string-matching trap",desc:"Your API returns { 'error': 'The email address is already in use' }. Your mobile client checks if (error.message.includes('already in use')) to show a specific UI message. You wordsmith the error to 'This email is taken' — the mobile client's conditional breaks, and it shows a generic error instead of helpful guidance. The fix: always return structured errors with a stable, documented error_code field that clients switch on, plus a human-readable message that clients can display but never parse programmatically. Example: { 'error': { 'code': 'email_already_exists', 'message': 'The email address is already in use', 'field': 'email', 'doc_url': 'https://docs.example.com/errors/email_already_exists' } }. Error codes are part of your API contract and should be versioned like any other field. RFC 7807 (Problem Details for HTTP APIs) is a good standard to follow."},
    {name:"Inconsistent naming and casing conventions",desc:"GET /users returns { 'firstName': 'Alice' } (camelCase). GET /organizations returns { 'org_name': 'Acme' } (snake_case). GET /invoices returns { 'InvoiceDate': '2024-01' } (PascalCase). Three endpoints, three conventions. Every client team wastes time figuring out the pattern for each endpoint. Pick one naming convention and enforce it everywhere: snake_case is the most common for JSON APIs (used by Stripe, GitHub, Twitter), camelCase is common in JavaScript-heavy ecosystems. Use a linter (Spectral for OpenAPI, graphql-eslint for GraphQL) to enforce naming rules in CI. Consistency is more important than which convention you choose."},
    {name:"Overloaded endpoints that try to do everything",desc:"PATCH /users/42 accepts 47 different fields including role changes, password resets, email verification, avatar upload, and preference updates — all in one endpoint. The authorization logic becomes a nightmare (can a regular user change their own role?), validation is complex (some fields are interdependent), and the endpoint is untestable. Separate semantically different operations into different endpoints: POST /users/42/change-password, POST /users/42/verify-email, PATCH /users/42/preferences. Each has clear authorization, clear validation, and clear intent. An API is a user interface — it should make the right thing obvious and the wrong thing hard."}
  ],
  examples:[
    {name:"Stripe's API — the gold standard that every API should aspire to",desc:"Stripe's API is consistently cited as the best-designed API in the industry, and studying it is the fastest way to internalize good API design principles. Key design decisions: (1) Versioning by date (Stripe-Version: 2024-06-20) — each account is pinned to the version it was created with; upgrades are explicit. Stripe maintains backward compatibility across dozens of versions simultaneously. (2) Idempotency keys on every mutating endpoint — every POST accepts an Idempotency-Key header, and retries with the same key return the original response. (3) Predictable, machine-readable error codes with human-readable messages and documentation URLs. (4) Expandable resources — GET /charges/ch_123?expand[]=customer returns the full customer object inline instead of just the ID, reducing round trips. (5) Consistent patterns across every endpoint: same pagination, same error format, same filtering, same naming. The investment in API design pays compound interest: Stripe's developer experience is frequently cited as the #1 reason companies choose Stripe over competitors, even when competitors offer lower transaction fees."},
    {name:"Twitter API v1 → v2 transition — the cost of getting v1 wrong",desc:"Twitter's v1 API evolved organically over years, accumulating inconsistencies: different endpoints used different authentication schemes, pagination was inconsistent, response formats varied, and rate limiting was unpredictable. By 2018, it was unmaintainable. The v2 overhaul was a multi-year project with breaking changes that killed many third-party applications (some of which had built businesses on Twitter's platform). Developers who had invested months integrating v1 were furious. The transition took 3+ years and is still not complete for all endpoints. Lessons: (1) Design v1 as if you'll maintain it for 10 years, because you might. (2) If you must do a major version, provide a generous migration window (Twitter gave ~2 years). (3) The organizational cost of a major API version is far higher than the engineering cost — partner relations, documentation, SDK updates, developer evangelism all need to be rebuilt."},
    {name:"GitHub's API — REST and GraphQL coexisting",desc:"GitHub offers both a REST API (v3) and a GraphQL API (v4) simultaneously. The REST API is simpler and works well for straightforward operations (create a repo, list issues). The GraphQL API shines for complex queries that would require many REST round trips (fetch a repo's pull requests with reviews, comments, and reviewer details in one query). GitHub didn't deprecate REST when they added GraphQL — they recognized that different consumers have different needs. The lesson: protocol choice isn't either/or. Offering multiple protocols for different use cases is a legitimate strategy, provided you can afford to maintain both. GitHub can because their user base justifies it; your startup probably can't — start with REST and add GraphQL only when you have demonstrated demand for flexible querying."},
    {name:"Twilio's API — designed for copy-paste success",desc:"Twilio's API design philosophy prioritizes 'time to first successful API call.' Their documentation includes copy-pasteable code samples in 6+ languages for every endpoint, and the API is designed so that the simplest possible request does something useful (sending an SMS requires exactly 3 fields). Error messages include the exact curl command to reproduce the issue. This developer-centric design made Twilio the default choice for communications APIs despite strong competitors. Lesson: API design isn't just about technical correctness — it's about the developer experience of the first 5 minutes."}
  ],
  levelUp:[
    {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">2 backend services needing to communicate, or first public API consumer (mobile app, partner integration) — the moment your API has consumers you don't fully control",action:"Formalize your API contract: adopt OpenAPI 3.0 specification and generate documentation from it (Swagger UI, Redoc). Add versioning to every endpoint (/v1/ prefix is simplest — add it to your router config and set up a URL rewrite rule so existing clients aren't broken). Implement idempotency keys on all mutating endpoints (POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE) using a Redis-backed dedup cache with a 24h TTL. Standardize error responses across all endpoints using a shared error handler middleware. How to do it concretely: install an OpenAPI linter like Spectral in CI that enforces naming conventions, required fields (error codes, pagination), and versioning prefixes. Create a shared API response envelope (e.g., { data: ..., meta: { pagination: ... }, errors: [...] }) and have all endpoints use it through a common serializer. For idempotency, create middleware that intercepts mutating requests, checks Redis for the Idempotency-Key, and returns the cached response if found — libraries like 'idempotent-request' (Node), 'idempotency-key' (Ruby), or a simple custom middleware will do."},
    {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">10 internal services calling each other, or API latency overhead from JSON serialization becoming measurable (>10ms per call), or multiple client types (web, mobile, partner) with divergent data needs making REST over-/under-fetching painful",action:"Introduce gRPC with Protocol Buffers for all internal service-to-service communication — the binary serialization is 5–10× smaller and 2–5× faster to parse than JSON, and code-generated clients provide compile-time type safety across services. Keep REST (or add GraphQL) for external consumers. Deploy a dedicated API gateway (Kong or Envoy) to centralize authentication, rate limiting, and request routing. Adopt a schema registry (Buf for Protobuf, Confluent Schema Registry for Avro) to enforce backward compatibility on every schema change in CI. How to do it concretely: start by defining .proto files for your hottest internal APIs (the ones called most frequently). Use buf lint and buf breaking in CI to prevent incompatible changes. Generate client and server stubs in your languages of choice (protoc-gen-go, grpc-tools for Node, grpc-java). For the gateway, deploy Kong (open source, Docker-based, plugin architecture) or Envoy (raw performance, used by Istio) — either can route external REST traffic to backend services while internal services talk gRPC directly. Set up the gateway with: JWT validation plugin (offload auth from services), rate-limiting plugin (per-consumer), and request-logging plugin (centralized access logs)."},
    {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"API latency SLO <5ms for hot paths, or throughput exceeds 1M RPS and JSON serialization/HTTP overhead is measurable at scale, or you need to serve API responses from 300+ global edge PoPs",action:"Move ultra-hot internal paths to custom binary protocols — FlatBuffers (zero-copy deserialization, no parsing step — used by Google for performance-critical paths) or Cap'n Proto (similar zero-copy approach) for paths where even Protobuf's decode time matters. Deploy HTTP/3 (QUIC) at the edge for client-facing APIs — it eliminates TCP head-of-line blocking and saves one RTT on connection establishment, which is a 10–30% improvement on mobile networks. For the highest-throughput paths, consider stateful persistent connections (custom protocol over TCP/QUIC) where the connection setup overhead of per-request HTTP is measurable. How to do it concretely: profile your API request lifecycle end-to-end to identify where time is actually spent (serialization? network? auth? routing?). For hot paths, replace Protobuf with FlatBuffers — the difference is FlatBuffers accesses serialized data in-place without a decode step, eliminating ~1–3ms of CPU per request at high throughput. For HTTP/3, enable it at your CDN/edge layer (Cloudflare supports it natively; Fastly supports it; AWS CloudFront has partial support) — clients that support QUIC will auto-negotiate. Internally, evaluate whether gRPC over QUIC (experimental but emerging) reduces tail latency on lossy internal networks."}
  ],
  children:[
    {name:"Protocol Selection",id:"api-proto",icon:"📡",phase:"API Layer",color:"#2563eb",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],short:"REST vs GraphQL vs gRPC vs WebSocket — each solves a different problem, and mixing is normal",
     detail:{
       what:"The wire protocol and serialization format that your API speaks. This isn't a religious choice — it's a technical one driven by your consumer needs, latency budget, and operational maturity. REST (HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/2 + JSON): the lingua franca of web APIs. Every language, framework, proxy, CDN, browser, and debugging tool speaks REST. The request/response model is simple: verb + URL + JSON body. The downside is rigidity — each endpoint returns a fixed shape, so clients often get too much data (over-fetching: you need the user's name but get 50 fields) or too little (under-fetching: you need the user + their orders + their reviews, requiring 3 separate requests). GraphQL (HTTP + JSON with a query language): Facebook's response to the over-/under-fetching problem. The client sends a query describing exactly what data it needs; the server resolves it and returns exactly that shape. One round trip for complex, nested data. Extraordinary for mobile apps on slow networks where round trips are expensive. The downside: you've given clients a query language, which means they can construct pathologically expensive queries if you don't add safeguards. gRPC (HTTP/2 + Protocol Buffers): Google's RPC framework. Messages are defined in .proto files, then code-generated into strongly-typed client and server stubs in 10+ languages. Protobuf binary serialization is 5–10× smaller than equivalent JSON and 3–5× faster to parse. HTTP/2 multiplexing means many concurrent requests over one connection. The downside: binary payloads are not human-readable (you can't debug with curl easily), browser support is poor (gRPC-Web exists but adds complexity), and many CDNs/proxies don't handle HTTP/2 streaming well. WebSocket (persistent TCP): a long-lived bidirectional connection between client and server. Server can push data to the client at any time without the client asking — essential for chat, live dashboards, collaborative editing, gaming, and real-time notifications. The downside: stateful connections are harder to load-balance (sticky sessions required), harder to scale (each connection consumes server memory), and don't work through all corporate proxies. Server-Sent Events (SSE) is a simpler one-way alternative (server→client only) that works over regular HTTP and automatically reconnects. The mature pattern: REST for external/public APIs, gRPC for internal service-to-service, WebSocket or SSE for real-time features. This isn't a compromise — it's the right tool for each job.",
       why:"Choosing the wrong protocol costs you in one of three ways. (1) Performance tax: REST/JSON between internal services at 50K RPS means you're spending significant CPU on JSON serialization/deserialization and significant bandwidth on verbose text payloads — gRPC would cut both by 5–10×. At scale, this translates to fewer servers needed and lower latency. (2) Developer experience tax: gRPC for a public mobile API means every consumer needs Protobuf tooling, HTTP/2 support, and binary debugging capabilities — the integration friction drives away developers who would have built on a simple REST API in an afternoon. (3) Round-trip tax: REST for a mobile app that needs deeply nested data (user → posts → comments → likes) means 4 sequential API calls on a 200ms mobile connection = 800ms minimum. GraphQL returns it all in one 200ms call. Each protocol excels at something specific: REST at simplicity and universality, GraphQL at flexible client-driven queries, gRPC at efficient service-to-service communication, and WebSocket at real-time push. The question isn't 'which is best?' — it's 'what does each consumer of my API actually need?' For most companies, the answer is a mix — and that's the correct answer.",
       numbers:"Latency comparison (typical end-to-end for a single request): REST/JSON ~20–200ms (depending on payload size, network, server processing — JSON serialization itself is ~1–5ms for typical payloads). gRPC/Protobuf ~5–50ms (binary serialization saves ~1–5ms, HTTP/2 multiplexing eliminates connection overhead, smaller payloads reduce network time). GraphQL ~20–200ms per request but replaces N REST calls with 1 (so effective latency for complex screens can be 3–5× better than REST). WebSocket push latency: <5ms server-to-client once the connection is established. Payload size: a typical API response (user profile with 20 fields) is ~2KB as JSON, ~200–400 bytes as Protobuf — 5–10× smaller. Over millions of requests per day, this bandwidth difference is significant ($0.09/GB for AWS egress). Round trips: a mobile screen that needs data from 4 REST endpoints requires 4 sequential calls × ~100ms mobile RTT = 400ms minimum. GraphQL serves it in 1 call = 100ms. This is why Facebook built GraphQL — their mobile app was making 15+ REST calls per screen on slow 3G connections in emerging markets."
     },
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Simplicity vs Efficiency",left:"REST: every developer knows it, every tool supports it, debug with curl in 10 seconds — but JSON payloads are verbose and each endpoint is a fixed shape",right:"gRPC: 5–10× smaller payloads, code-generated type-safe clients, HTTP/2 multiplexing — but binary is hard to debug, browser support is limited, and you need Protobuf tooling",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Flexibility vs Predictability",left:"GraphQL: clients compose arbitrary queries, request exactly what they need, self-documenting schema via introspection — but query cost is unpredictable, N+1 DB queries are easy to create, and authorization per-field is complex",right:"gRPC: strict .proto schema means both sides know exactly what to expect, code generation catches contract violations at compile time — but clients can't request partial data, and schema evolution requires careful management",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Universality vs Performance for real-time",left:"REST + polling: works everywhere, through every proxy, with every tool — but polling wastes bandwidth (95% of polls return no new data) and latency equals your poll interval",right:"WebSocket/SSE: instant server push, <5ms delivery — but requires persistent connections (memory cost), sticky load balancing, and doesn't traverse all corporate proxies",pos:0.5}
     ],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"GraphQL N+1 query problem — the silent performance killer",desc:"A client queries { users { posts { comments } } }. The users resolver fetches 20 users. For each user, the posts resolver makes a separate DB query. For each post, the comments resolver makes another query. Result: 1 + 20 + (20 × 5) = 121 database queries for one GraphQL request. The client sees one API call; the server sees a database meltdown. The fix: the DataLoader pattern (originally by Facebook). DataLoader batches and deduplicates individual lookups within a single tick of the event loop: instead of 20 separate 'get posts for user X' queries, it collects all 20 user IDs and makes one 'get posts for users [1,2,...,20]' query. Libraries: dataloader (JavaScript, the original), Strawberry DataLoader (Python), graphql-batch (Ruby). This is not optional — any GraphQL server without DataLoader will have catastrophic N+1 performance on nested queries."},
       {name:"GraphQL exposed to the public without query depth and complexity limits",desc:"An attacker (or a naive client) sends: { users { posts { comments { author { posts { comments { author { posts ... } } } } } } } } — a 50-level deep nested query. Your server dutifully tries to resolve it, generating millions of DB queries and consuming all available memory. Your API is now a denial-of-service weapon against yourself. Defenses (all are required for a public GraphQL API): (1) Max query depth: reject queries deeper than 10–15 levels (graphql-depth-limit library). (2) Query complexity analysis: assign a cost to each field and reject queries above a total cost threshold (graphql-query-complexity). (3) Per-client rate limits: limit total query cost per client per minute, not just request count. (4) Persisted queries (optional but powerful): clients register queries ahead of time; the server only executes known queries — blocks all arbitrary queries. Apollo Server and Hasura both support this. Facebook's production GraphQL endpoint uses persisted queries exclusively — no arbitrary queries from clients reach production."},
       {name:"gRPC for public mobile APIs — fighting the infrastructure",desc:"gRPC requires HTTP/2 and binary Protobuf tooling. Many older corporate proxies and firewalls inspect HTTP traffic and can't handle HTTP/2 binary frames — they silently drop or corrupt them. CDNs like CloudFront and Cloudflare have limited gRPC support (Cloudflare added it recently, but it's still not as well-tested as HTTP/1.1). Mobile debugging is harder because you can't just open Chrome DevTools and read the payloads. For public-facing APIs (especially mobile), use REST or GraphQL — the universality and debuggability are worth more than the serialization savings. Reserve gRPC for internal service-to-service communication where you control both ends and the network. The exception: if your mobile app uses a gRPC-generated client library (common in Google's ecosystem), gRPC-Web can bridge the gap using an Envoy proxy that translates between gRPC-Web and native gRPC."},
       {name:"WebSocket without fallback — losing corporate users",desc:"You implement chat using raw WebSocket. Works perfectly in development, works perfectly on home WiFi. But 10% of your enterprise customers are behind corporate proxies that intercept and block WebSocket upgrade requests. Those users get a spinning loader forever. The solution: use a transport library that automatically falls back to long-polling or SSE when WebSocket isn't available. Socket.IO (JavaScript — the most popular, handles reconnection, rooms, namespacing, and automatic fallback), Ably (managed, global, message guarantees), Pusher (managed, simple pub/sub). If you use raw WebSocket, at minimum implement detection: attempt WebSocket connection with a 5-second timeout, fall back to SSE or long-polling on failure, and log the fallback rate to understand your users' network environments."},
       {name:"Not using server-sent events (SSE) when they'd suffice",desc:"You need to push notifications from server to client — new messages, live scores, stock prices. You reach for WebSocket because 'that's how you do real-time.' But your data flow is one-directional: server → client only. SSE (Server-Sent Events) does this more simply: it's plain HTTP (works through every proxy), auto-reconnects on disconnect, supports event types and IDs natively, and requires zero special infrastructure. WebSocket's bidirectionality is only needed when the client also pushes data (chat, collaborative editing). For notification feeds, live dashboards, and activity streams, SSE is simpler and more robust. SSE is supported in all modern browsers and trivially implementable in any HTTP framework."},
       {name:"Choosing GraphQL because it's modern rather than because you have the problem it solves",desc:"GraphQL solves a specific problem: clients with widely varied data needs making multiple round trips. If you have one web app and one mobile app built by your own team, and they both need roughly the same data, GraphQL's overhead (schema design, resolver architecture, DataLoader, query complexity limits, caching complexity) provides minimal benefit over REST with well-designed endpoints. GraphQL shines when: you have 5+ different client types (iOS, Android, web, watch, partner), each needing different data subsets; or your data is deeply nested and clients frequently need varied depths; or you're building a platform where external developers write their own queries. If none of these apply, REST is simpler, better cached, and better tooled."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Facebook's GraphQL origin story — solving a real problem",desc:"Facebook built GraphQL in 2012 because their mobile News Feed needed wildly varied subsets of user profile data (name, photo, mutual friends, recent posts, etc.) depending on the feed card type, device capability, and connection speed. The REST approach required either: (a) one endpoint returning everything (2MB response for a card that needed 50 bytes), or (b) dozens of specialized endpoints per card type (unmaintainable). On slow 2G networks in emerging markets, round trips cost 500ms each, so multiple REST calls were devastating. GraphQL solved both: one request, exactly the fields needed, one round trip. This is the canonical use case for GraphQL: highly varied client needs over slow networks with expensive round trips. If this isn't your situation, GraphQL may be overhead without benefit."},
       {name:"Google's gRPC (and Stubby) everywhere internally",desc:"Google standardized all internal RPC on Stubby (gRPC's predecessor) in the 2000s and open-sourced the design as gRPC in 2015. Every internal service at Google communicates via Protocol Buffers over Stubby/gRPC. The benefits at Google's scale are enormous: strong typing via .proto files means contract violations are caught at compile time (not at 3am in production), code generation in 10+ languages means teams using Go, Java, Python, and C++ can interoperate seamlessly, and binary serialization saves millions of dollars in bandwidth and CPU across billions of daily requests. gRPC's design decisions all trace back to Google's scale: bidirectional streaming (for Google's internal distributed databases), pluggable authentication (for Google's internal security model), and built-in deadlines/cancellation propagation (essential when requests fan out to hundreds of services)."},
       {name:"Shopify's REST-first approach for developer ecosystem",desc:"Shopify provides a REST API as the primary integration point for their 1M+ merchants and thousands of app developers. Despite also offering a GraphQL API (the Storefront API), they've kept REST as the default because their developer audience ranges from solo merchants writing simple integrations to large agencies building complex apps. REST's universality (every developer has used it, every tutorial teaches it) maximizes the ecosystem size. GraphQL is offered as an option for advanced use cases (complex product queries, storefront customization). This dual-protocol strategy maximizes developer reach while offering power users the flexibility they need."},
       {name:"Discord using WebSocket + REST hybrid",desc:"Discord uses WebSocket for real-time message delivery, presence updates, and typing indicators (data that must push instantly). But message history, channel management, and server settings use REST (data that's fetched on-demand, not pushed). This hybrid is the most common production pattern: REST for request-response operations where the client initiates, WebSocket for server-initiated push where latency matters. They also use ETF (Erlang Term Format) as an alternative serialization to JSON over their WebSocket connection for bandwidth reduction — demonstrating that protocol optimization can happen at the serialization layer, not just the transport layer."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"Public/mobile API, <10K RPS, 1–3 backend services",rec:"REST + JSON. Full stop. Start here always — it's the path of least resistance with the highest compatibility. Use OpenAPI 3.0 (formerly Swagger) to define your API contract and auto-generate interactive documentation (Swagger UI or Redoc — both free and excellent). Write the spec first (contract-first design) before writing implementation code — this forces you to think about the API as a consumer would experience it, not as your database is shaped. Technology choices and their tradeoffs: Express.js (Node.js — minimal, flexible, largest ecosystem of middleware; weakness: no opinions, you make every decision yourself; best when you want full control). FastAPI (Python — auto-generates OpenAPI docs from type hints, async-first, excellent performance for Python; weakness: smaller ecosystem than Flask/Django for web apps; best for API-only services). Rails API mode (Ruby — convention-over-configuration, mature serializers, built-in pagination; weakness: Ruby runtime is slower than Go/Node for pure throughput; best when developer productivity matters more than raw performance). NestJS (TypeScript — opinionated, decorator-based, built-in validation/serialization; weakness: steeper learning curve than Express; best for teams that want structure). For documentation: OpenAPI 3.0 spec + Redoc (beautiful auto-generated docs) or Stoplight (collaborative API design platform). Postman for manual testing and API collection sharing.",tools:["Express.js REST","FastAPI","Rails API","NestJS","OpenAPI 3.0","Redoc","Postman"]},
       medium:{range:"Mixed public + internal traffic, 10K–100K RPS, 5–20 services",rec:"REST for public APIs (keep it simple for external consumers). Add gRPC for internal service-to-service calls where the performance difference is measurable — internal calls that happen millions of times daily benefit from 5–10× smaller payloads and type-safe code-generated clients. Consider GraphQL if you have multiple client types (web, iOS, Android, partner) with genuinely different data needs — but only if you're willing to invest in the N+1 prevention (DataLoader) and query safety (depth limiting, complexity analysis) infrastructure. Don't add GraphQL because it's trendy; add it because your clients are making 5+ REST calls per screen and you've measured the round-trip cost. Technology comparison: gRPC (Google — the industry standard for internal RPC; supports streaming, deadlines, cancellation propagation; tooling: buf for linting and breaking change detection, BloomRPC or grpcui for manual testing). GraphQL servers: Apollo Server (JavaScript — most popular, rich ecosystem, Apollo Studio for monitoring/schema management; weakness: performance overhead of the Apollo runtime), Hasura (auto-generates GraphQL from Postgres — fastest path to GraphQL but less control over resolver logic), Strawberry (Python — modern, type-hint based), graphql-ruby (Ruby — mature, used by GitHub and Shopify). For API testing: Postman (REST + GraphQL), Insomnia (open-source alternative), and contract testing with Pact.",tools:["gRPC + Protobuf","Apollo Server (GraphQL)","REST","Postman","buf","Hasura"]},
       large:{range:"Internal service mesh, 100K–500K RPS, 20–200 services",rec:"gRPC is the standard for all internal service-to-service calls at this scale — the performance benefits compound across hundreds of services. REST or GraphQL remain for client-facing APIs, fronted by an API gateway. WebSocket or SSE for real-time features (chat, notifications, live updates). A schema registry becomes essential: every .proto file or GraphQL schema is version-controlled, and CI rejects any change that breaks backward compatibility. Technology choices: gRPC + Protobuf with Buf (schema registry — linting, breaking change detection, code generation, all in one tool; $0 for open-source, Buf Schema Registry for managed hosting). Apollo Federation (GraphQL — composes multiple service-specific GraphQL schemas into one unified supergraph that clients query; used by Netflix, Expedia, Volvo; weakness: adds complexity and a federation gateway hop). Connect RPC (by Buf — a modern alternative to gRPC that's fully compatible with gRPC clients but also works with plain HTTP/1.1 and curl, making it easier to debug; gaining rapid adoption). For WebSocket at this scale: use a dedicated real-time tier (Centrifugo, Socket.IO cluster, or custom) rather than bolting WebSocket onto your application servers.",tools:["gRPC + Protobuf + Buf","Apollo Federation","Connect RPC","WebSocket tier","Centrifugo"]},
       hyper:{range:"Custom protocols for hot paths, >500K RPS, global edge serving",rec:"gRPC remains the backbone for internal communication. REST/GraphQL for developer-facing APIs. For the hottest paths (ad serving, game state sync, financial trading) where even Protobuf's ~1ms decode time matters: FlatBuffers or Cap'n Proto for zero-copy deserialization (access fields directly from the serialized buffer without a parse step — 10–100× faster decode than Protobuf for large messages). QUIC/HTTP3 at the edge for client-facing traffic (saves 1 RTT on connection setup, eliminates TCP head-of-line blocking — measured 10–30% improvement in page load times on mobile). Custom binary protocols over raw TCP or QUIC for ultra-specialized paths (game server netcode, exchange matching engines) where no general-purpose protocol is fast enough. Technology choices: FlatBuffers (Google — zero-copy, no parsing step, C++/Java/Go/Rust; weakness: more complex schema evolution than Protobuf, less tooling). Cap'n Proto (by Kenton Varda, creator of Protobuf v2 — similar zero-copy approach; weakness: smaller community). QUIC implementations: quiche (Cloudflare, Rust), msquic (Microsoft, C), quic-go (Go). HTTP/3 support: Cloudflare (native), Fastly (native), AWS CloudFront (partial). For custom protocols: typically built in Rust or C++ for memory safety and performance, using io_uring (Linux) or epoll for efficient I/O.",tools:["gRPC","FlatBuffers","Cap'n Proto","QUIC/HTTP3","custom binary protocols","io_uring"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Internal service calls exceed >10K/day (the serialization/deserialization overhead becomes measurable) or average payload size >1MB (JSON bloat becomes a real bandwidth cost) or you've added a second client type (mobile app alongside web) with different data needs",action:"Add gRPC for internal service-to-service communication while keeping REST for external consumers. Start with schema-first design: define your .proto files first, review them like you'd review an API spec, then generate client and server stubs. How to do it: (1) Install buf (buf.build) — it replaces protoc with a faster, more user-friendly Protobuf compiler that includes linting and breaking change detection. (2) Define your .proto files for the 2–3 hottest internal APIs first. (3) Run buf generate to produce client/server code in your languages. (4) Add buf lint and buf breaking to CI so every PR that modifies a .proto file is checked for style and compatibility. (5) Internal services call each other via gRPC; external clients still use REST via your existing API. The migration is incremental — you don't need to convert everything at once."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">10 internal services communicating (the overhead of maintaining REST clients for each is significant) or internal API latency exceeds 50ms (JSON overhead is a measurable contributor) or schema drift between services is causing production bugs",action:"Standardize on gRPC for all internal traffic. Deploy a service mesh (Istio or Linkerd) that handles mTLS, traffic management, retries, and observability at the network layer so services don't need to implement these individually. Establish a schema registry (Buf Schema Registry or Confluent Schema Registry) as the single source of truth for all API contracts. How to do it: (1) Mandate that every new internal service uses gRPC — no exceptions. Existing services migrate opportunistically (when you're already modifying a service, convert its APIs). (2) Deploy the service mesh incrementally (Linkerd is simpler to adopt; Istio is more powerful but complex) — start with mTLS and observability, add traffic management later. (3) Set up the schema registry and add CI rules: every PR that modifies a .proto or .avro file must pass compatibility checks against the registry. Breaking changes are blocked unless explicitly versioned. (4) For client-facing APIs, evaluate whether Apollo Federation makes sense (it does if you have 5+ teams contributing to the client-facing API surface)."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"API latency SLO <5ms for critical hot paths (Protobuf decode time is a measurable fraction) or throughput exceeds 1M RPS (HTTP overhead per request adds up) or you're serving users globally from 100+ edge PoPs and need sub-10ms response times",action:"Identify the specific hot paths where standard gRPC/Protobuf is the bottleneck (profile with flamegraphs — is time spent in protobuf decode? in HTTP framing? in TLS handshake?). For decode-bound paths, switch to FlatBuffers or Cap'n Proto (zero-copy access eliminates the decode step entirely). For connection-setup-bound paths, deploy HTTP/3 (QUIC) at the edge — it saves 1 RTT per new connection and eliminates TCP head-of-line blocking. For throughput-bound paths, consider persistent stateful connections with custom framing. How to do it: (1) Profile each hot path's request lifecycle with distributed tracing + flamegraphs to identify where time is actually spent. (2) For FlatBuffers migration: define .fbs schema files (similar to .proto), generate accessors, and replace Protobuf on the specific hot paths. Don't convert everything — only the paths where profiling shows decode time is significant. (3) For HTTP/3: enable it at your CDN layer first (Cloudflare: one toggle; Fastly: configuration change) — clients that support QUIC will auto-negotiate. Measure the impact on mobile users specifically (they benefit most from QUIC's connection migration and loss recovery). (4) For custom protocols: only build these for genuinely extreme cases (game netcode, HFT) where no general-purpose protocol is fast enough — the maintenance burden is significant."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"API Gateway",id:"api-gw",icon:"🚪",phase:"API Layer",color:"#2563eb",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],short:"None → Nginx → managed gateway → global custom edge — the single front door for all API traffic",
     detail:{
       what:"An API gateway is a single entry point for all incoming API traffic — the 'front door' of your system. It sits between clients and your backend services, handling cross-cutting concerns that would otherwise be duplicated in every service: (1) Authentication — validate JWT tokens, API keys, or OAuth tokens once at the edge instead of in each service. (2) Rate limiting — enforce per-client, per-IP, per-endpoint request limits to prevent abuse and ensure fair usage. (3) SSL/TLS termination — handle the encryption/decryption overhead at the gateway so backend services communicate in plaintext (or mTLS) internally. (4) Request routing — direct /api/users to the user service, /api/orders to the order service, based on URL path, headers, or query parameters. (5) Logging and observability — centralized access logs, request tracing, and metrics collection. (6) Request/response transformation — add headers, rewrite URLs, transform payloads (e.g., XML↔JSON for legacy integrations). (7) Traffic management — canary routing (send 1% of traffic to the new version), A/B testing (route by user cohort), request shadowing (duplicate traffic to a test environment for comparison). Without a gateway, each service must implement all of these individually — inconsistent behavior, duplicated code, and security gaps are inevitable. With a gateway, you change auth logic in one place and it applies everywhere, you add rate limiting with one configuration change, and you get canary deployments for free.",
       why:"The gateway's value increases with the number of backend services. With 2 services, the overhead of a gateway barely pays for itself. With 20 services, the alternative (each service implementing its own auth, rate limiting, SSL, logging, and routing) means 20 different implementations of the same cross-cutting concerns, maintained by 20 different teams, each with slightly different bugs and security gaps. The gateway centralizes these: one team, one implementation, one configuration. But the gateway is also a double-edged sword: it's a single point of entry, which means it's a single point of failure. If the gateway goes down, your entire API is down — regardless of how healthy your backend services are. This means the gateway must be the most reliable, most monitored, most redundant component in your system. Always run at least 2 gateway instances behind a load balancer (even in development). Health-check them aggressively (every 5 seconds). And keep the gateway thin: routing, auth, rate limiting, logging. The moment business logic creeps into the gateway, it becomes both the bottleneck and the risk for every service — and deploys to the gateway become terrifying because a bug affects everything.",
       numbers:"Latency added by a gateway hop: 1–5ms for managed gateways (AWS API Gateway: ~5ms typical, Kong: ~2–4ms, Nginx: ~1ms). Tuned custom Envoy gateways achieve <1ms overhead. Throughput per gateway node: AWS API Gateway handles ~10K RPS per region by default (soft limit, raisable to 100K+). Kong handles ~30K–100K RPS per node depending on plugin count. Envoy proxy handles 100K–1M+ RPS per node (C++, extremely efficient). For high-availability: always run N+1 gateway instances (at least 2) behind a load balancer. If you need >100K RPS, scale gateway nodes horizontally — most gateways are stateless and scale linearly. The gateway is also where you terminate TLS — this offloads the crypto overhead from your backend services. Modern hardware with AES-NI instruction set handles TLS termination with negligible overhead."
     },
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Centralization vs Latency",left:"One hop for auth, rate limiting, logging, routing — consistent behavior, single point of configuration, enables platform features like canary routing",right:"Every request pays 1–5ms of additional latency for the gateway hop — at hyper scale, this adds up to significant aggregate latency",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Managed vs Self-hosted",left:"Managed gateway (AWS API Gateway, Apigee): zero operational burden, automatic scaling, built-in monitoring — but limited customization, potential vendor lock-in, and per-request pricing that gets expensive at scale ($3.50/M requests for AWS API Gateway)",right:"Self-hosted gateway (Kong, Envoy, Nginx): full control, custom plugins, predictable cost — but you're responsible for scaling, updating, monitoring, and HA of the gateway itself",pos:0.4},
       {axis:"Thin gateway vs Smart gateway",left:"Thin: routing + auth + rate limit only — fast, reliable, simple to maintain, easy to reason about",right:"Smart: request transformation, response aggregation, business logic, complex routing — more powerful but the gateway becomes a deployment bottleneck and a reliability risk for the entire system",pos:0.3}
     ],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Business logic in the gateway — the gateway-as-application antipattern",desc:"The gateway started as 'just routes and auth.' Then someone added request body validation. Then someone added response field filtering for different API versions. Then someone added a caching layer. Then someone added a 'combine these two service responses into one' aggregation. Now the gateway has 5,000 lines of business logic, deploys require coordinating with 3 teams, and a bug in the gateway takes down every API endpoint simultaneously. Keep the gateway thin: routing, authentication, rate limiting, SSL termination, request logging, and header manipulation. Everything else belongs in the services. If you find yourself writing if/else logic in the gateway that depends on business rules, stop and put it in a service."},
       {name:"Gateway as single point of failure — the ironic outage",desc:"You add a gateway to improve reliability. The gateway crashes. Now every API endpoint is down, even though all backend services are perfectly healthy. The irony of adding a reliability component that becomes your biggest reliability risk. Prevention: (1) Always run multiple gateway instances behind a load balancer (minimum 2, ideally 3+). (2) Health-check gateway instances every 5 seconds; remove unhealthy instances from the pool within 15 seconds. (3) The gateway's own deployment should be the most careful in the system — canary deploys, automated rollback on error rate increase, and separate CI/CD from backend services. (4) Monitor gateway-specific metrics: p99 latency, error rate, connection count, memory usage. If the gateway itself is showing latency, you have a problem that affects everyone."},
       {name:"No bypass for internal traffic — taxing your own services",desc:"Service A calls Service B through the public API gateway, paying the full latency (5ms gateway hop + auth check + rate limit check + logging) even though both services are on the same internal network and already authenticated. Internal service-to-service traffic should NOT traverse the public gateway. Instead, use: (1) Direct service-to-service communication via internal DNS or service discovery (Consul, Kubernetes service names). (2) A service mesh (Istio, Linkerd) for internal traffic management, mTLS, and observability — this gives you the gateway benefits (auth, observability, traffic management) without the gateway hop and without mixing internal and external traffic. (3) If you must route internal traffic through a shared component, use a separate internal gateway with lighter-weight processing."},
       {name:"Not accounting for the gateway's own limits",desc:"AWS API Gateway has an account-level throttle of 10,000 RPS per region by default. Your service can handle 50,000 RPS. On your biggest traffic day, the gateway itself becomes the bottleneck and returns 429s while your backend servers idle. Always know and test your gateway's throughput limits. AWS API Gateway: 10K default, raisable via support ticket (takes days — not something to discover during a traffic spike). Kong: limited by your hardware, typically 30–100K RPS per node. Envoy: 100K–1M+ RPS per node. Load test through the gateway, not around it."},
       {name:"Gateway configuration drift across environments",desc:"The staging gateway has different auth rules than production because someone manually configured it. A feature works in staging, breaks in production because the gateway routing rule is different. Solution: config-as-code for the gateway — store all gateway configuration in version control (Kong has declarative YAML config via decK, Envoy uses xDS API or static YAML, AWS API Gateway has CloudFormation/Terraform support). Deploy gateway config through the same CI/CD pipeline as application code."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"Netflix Zuul → custom gateway — the typical evolution path",desc:"Netflix originally built Zuul (Java-based) as their API gateway, handling authentication, routing, and traffic management for all of Netflix's API traffic. They open-sourced Zuul 1, which became widely adopted. But as Netflix's scale grew (and their requirements became more specialized — dynamic routing based on device type, A/B testing at the request level, fine-grained traffic shaping), they built Zuul 2 with async non-blocking I/O for better throughput, and eventually moved to even more custom solutions for specific traffic types. This demonstrates the typical gateway evolution: start with your framework's built-in routing → managed gateway when you have multiple services → open-source gateway when you need customization → custom gateway when no off-the-shelf solution meets your extreme requirements. Most companies never need to go past the 'open-source gateway' stage."},
       {name:"AWS API Gateway throttling surprise — know your limits",desc:"Multiple teams have been caught during traffic spikes by AWS API Gateway's account-level throttle (10K RPS per region default). The symptoms are confusing: your backend services show low utilization and no errors, but clients are getting 429 responses. The gateway itself is the bottleneck. AWS allows you to request limit increases, but the process takes days — it's a support ticket, not an API call. Lessons: (1) Always load test through the gateway, not around it. (2) Know the default limits of every managed service in your path. (3) Request limit increases proactively before known traffic events, not reactively during them."},
       {name:"Kong as the Swiss Army knife gateway",desc:"Kong is the most popular open-source API gateway, built on Nginx/OpenResty with a Lua plugin system. It handles authentication (JWT, OAuth2, API keys), rate limiting, logging, request transformation, and more through a plugin architecture. Kong Gateway (open source) is free; Kong Konnect (managed) adds a control plane UI, analytics, and enterprise support. Strengths: huge plugin ecosystem, battle-tested at scale (used by Nasdaq, King, Samsung), declarative configuration via decK. Weaknesses: Lua plugin development is niche (fewer developers available), and performance degrades with many active plugins (each adds ~0.5–1ms). Alternative: Envoy proxy — higher raw performance (C++), used as the data plane in Istio and many service meshes, but less approachable for simple gateway use cases."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"1–2 backend services — a separate gateway is overkill",rec:"Use your web framework's built-in routing — Express routes, FastAPI path operations, Rails routes. These already handle path-based routing within one application. SSL via Let's Encrypt (free, auto-renewing certificates) on Nginx or Caddy as your reverse proxy. Caddy is notable: it auto-provisions and auto-renews HTTPS certificates with zero configuration — just point your domain at it and it handles TLS automatically. No separate gateway until you have >2 backend services, because the operational cost of running and maintaining a gateway exceeds its benefits when you only have one service behind it. Technology choices: Nginx (the most deployed reverse proxy in the world — battle-tested, extensive documentation, huge community; weakness: config syntax is cryptic, reloads can be slow). Caddy (Go-based, automatic HTTPS, simple config, modern; weakness: smaller community than Nginx, fewer third-party modules). Traefik (Go-based, auto-discovers services from Docker/Kubernetes labels, built-in dashboard; weakness: configuration can be confusing with its dual static/dynamic model). All three handle basic reverse proxying, SSL termination, and simple load balancing.",tools:["Nginx","Caddy","Traefik","Let's Encrypt"]},
       medium:{range:"2–20 backend services — time for a real gateway",rec:"Deploy a managed or self-hosted API gateway to centralize authentication, rate limiting, SSL, and routing. At this stage, avoid building a custom gateway — the operational burden isn't worth it when battle-tested options exist. Technology comparison: AWS API Gateway (fully managed, auto-scales, native integration with Lambda/AWS services, built-in throttling and caching; weakness: 10K RPS default limit, $3.50/M requests pricing gets expensive above ~50M requests/month, 29ms cold start on regional endpoints). Kong Gateway (open-source, self-hosted on Docker/K8s, plugin architecture for auth/rate-limit/logging/transforms, declarative config via decK; weakness: requires you to run and maintain it, Lua plugin development is niche). Azure API Management (managed, policy engine for transforms, developer portal built-in; weakness: Azure lock-in, slower to deploy changes). Google Apigee (feature-rich, analytics, developer portal; weakness: expensive, complex). For most medium-scale teams: Kong (self-hosted) if you want control and have ops capacity, or AWS API Gateway if you want zero ops and your traffic is <50M requests/month.",tools:["AWS API Gateway","Kong Gateway","Nginx Plus","Azure API Management","Apigee"]},
       large:{range:"20–500 services — the gateway is critical infrastructure",rec:"High-performance gateway with configuration-as-code. At this scale, the gateway handles 100K+ RPS and supports advanced traffic management: per-service routing rules, canary traffic splitting (route 1% of requests to new service version), WebSocket proxying, request/response transformation, and per-endpoint rate limits. Technology comparison: Kong Enterprise (adds rate limiting with Redis backend, dev portal, analytics, RBAC — $250K+/year enterprise license; or use the open-source version with manual plugin setup). Envoy proxy (C++, extremely high performance, used as the data plane in Istio — handles 1M+ RPS per node; supports dynamic configuration via xDS API, enabling real-time routing changes without restarts; weakness: configuration is verbose and has a learning curve). AWS API Gateway v2 (HTTP APIs — lower latency than v1, lower cost at $1.00/M requests, but fewer features). Cloudflare Workers (serverless edge compute — run gateway logic at 300+ PoPs globally at <1ms, $0.50/M requests; excellent for auth, routing, header manipulation at the edge; weakness: limited compute time per request, not ideal for complex transformations). For most large-scale deployments: Envoy as the data plane with a control plane (either Istio or custom) for dynamic configuration.",tools:["Kong Enterprise","Envoy proxy","AWS API Gateway v2","Cloudflare Workers"]},
       hyper:{range:"500+ services, global traffic, <1ms gateway overhead required",rec:"Custom global gateway deployed at every Point of Presence (PoP). The gateway runs at the network edge, within 10ms of every user globally. Configuration is pushed in real-time via xDS protocol (Envoy's discovery service API) — a routing change takes effect at all PoPs within seconds, not minutes. Per-edge rate limiting (using local counters with async global reconciliation) prevents abuse without adding cross-region latency. BGP anycast ensures user traffic routes to the nearest PoP automatically. Technology approach: Envoy as the base (it's what most hyper-scale companies build on) with custom xDS control plane for dynamic configuration. Cloudflare Workers/Fastly Compute@Edge if you'd rather outsource the edge network (300+ PoPs that would cost hundreds of millions to build yourself). For the most extreme cases: custom gateway in Rust or C++ using io_uring for maximum I/O efficiency, DPDK for kernel-bypass networking, and custom TLS termination with hardware acceleration. Companies at this level: Cloudflare itself (custom Nginx fork + Rust), Netflix (custom Zuul 2 + Envoy), Uber (custom Envoy-based edge). The common pattern: Envoy as the foundation, custom control plane for your specific routing/auth/rate-limit needs.",tools:["Custom Envoy + xDS control plane","Cloudflare Workers","Fastly Compute@Edge","custom Rust/C++ gateway"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">2 backend services that need shared authentication, or you're implementing rate limiting and find yourself copy-pasting the same middleware into multiple services, or you need centralized access logging for compliance",action:"Deploy a dedicated API gateway. For teams on AWS with <50M requests/month: AWS API Gateway is the fastest path (managed, zero ops, native IAM integration). For teams wanting more control: deploy Kong on Docker (docker pull kong/kong-gateway) with the JWT auth plugin and rate-limiting plugin. How to do it: (1) Set up the gateway with health checks against each backend service. (2) Migrate external traffic routing from your Nginx/Caddy reverse proxy to the gateway, one endpoint group at a time (start with /api/users, then /api/orders, etc.). (3) Move authentication from per-service middleware to the gateway's JWT validation plugin — each service now receives a validated X-User-ID header instead of processing the token itself. (4) Add rate limiting at the gateway (100 req/min per API key for free tier, 10K/min for paid). (5) Centralized access logging: forward gateway logs to your log aggregator (Datadog, CloudWatch, ELK). Internal service-to-service calls should NOT go through this gateway — use direct HTTP/gRPC calls with service discovery."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">20 services behind the gateway (routing config is getting complex), or you need canary deployments (route 1% of traffic to new version), or the gateway's throughput is approaching its limits at peak traffic",action:"Move to a high-performance gateway with configuration-as-code. If you're already using Kong: adopt decK for declarative config management (store gateway config in YAML, deploy via CI/CD). If you need more performance: deploy Envoy with a control plane (Istio or custom). How to do it: (1) Export current gateway config to version-controlled files (YAML/JSON). (2) Set up CI/CD for gateway config: changes go through PR review and automated testing before deployment. (3) Integrate service discovery (Consul, Kubernetes DNS) so the gateway automatically discovers new services — no manual endpoint configuration. (4) Implement canary routing: gateway routes 1% of traffic to the new service version based on a header or random sampling; monitoring compares error rates between canary and stable; automated rollback if canary error rate exceeds threshold. (5) Separate the internal traffic path: service mesh (Linkerd/Istio) handles service-to-service, gateway handles only external traffic."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Gateway itself is becoming the throughput bottleneck (>500K RPS), or gateway latency is a measurable fraction of your end-to-end SLO, or you need sub-50ms response times globally (requiring edge-deployed gateway logic)",action:"Deploy gateway logic at the edge. How to do it depends on your approach: (A) Cloudflare Workers / Fastly Compute@Edge route: move auth validation, rate limiting, and routing logic to edge workers that run at 300+ PoPs. This is the fastest path to global edge — you get the PoP network without building it. Implementation: write your gateway logic as a Worker script, deploy via Wrangler CLI, and point your DNS at Cloudflare. (B) Custom Envoy edge route: deploy Envoy proxies at your own PoPs (or in multiple cloud regions) with a custom xDS control plane that pushes configuration changes in real-time. Use anycast BGP so user traffic automatically routes to the nearest Envoy instance. Implementation: this requires network engineering expertise (BGP, anycast, PoP deployment) — only pursue if you have a network team or if your traffic justifies the investment ($1M+/month cloud spend typically). (C) Hybrid: Cloudflare/Fastly for the edge network, custom Envoy for the origin gateway. Edge handles TLS termination, DDoS, basic rate limiting, static caching; origin gateway handles service routing, auth, and dynamic rate limiting."}
     ],
     children:[]},

    {name:"Rate Limiting",id:"api-rate",icon:"🚦",phase:"API Layer",color:"#2563eb",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],short:"Per-user, per-IP, per-service rate control — the cheapest insurance against both attacks and accidents",
     detail:{
       what:"Rate limiting restricts how many requests a client can make within a time window. It's three things simultaneously: (1) Protection — prevents one misbehaving client (whether malicious attacker or buggy code) from consuming all your backend capacity and creating an outage for everyone else. (2) Fairness — ensures that one tenant's heavy usage doesn't degrade the experience for other tenants in a shared system. (3) Monetization — enables tier-based pricing in commercial APIs (free=100 req/min, pro=10K/min, enterprise=100K/min). Rate limiting operates at multiple levels: per-IP (anti-abuse — stops DDoS and brute force), per-user/API-key (fair usage — each authenticated client gets their quota), per-endpoint (resource protection — expensive endpoints like /search get tighter limits than cheap endpoints like /health), and global (circuit breaker — overall system capacity protection). The algorithms determine how limits are enforced: token bucket (a bucket fills with tokens at a steady rate; each request consumes a token; when empty, requests are rejected — allows bursts up to bucket capacity while enforcing average rate), sliding window (count requests in a rolling time window — more accurate than fixed windows, slightly more memory), fixed window (count requests per calendar minute/hour — simplest but allows double-rate at window boundaries), and GCRA (Generic Cell Rate Algorithm — the most mathematically elegant, used by Cloudflare and Stripe, equivalent to a leaky bucket). All of these answer the same question: 'should this request be allowed through, or should it be rejected with a 429 Too Many Requests?'",
       why:"Without rate limiting, your system is one infinite loop away from an outage. Consider: a mobile developer ships a bug that retries a failed request in a tight loop. One user's phone generates 1,000 requests per second. With 100,000 users who update the app, you're suddenly receiving 100 million requests per second from your own customers. Without rate limiting, your servers try to handle all of them, saturate, and crash — taking down every user, not just the ones with the buggy app. Rate limiting would have capped each client at, say, 100 requests per minute, and the buggy app would have received 429 responses while everyone else continued normally. This exact scenario has caused real production outages at major companies. Even well-meaning clients can overwhelm you: a partner integration that queues requests during a maintenance window and replays them all at once when your API comes back ('thundering herd'). Rate limits are also the mechanism that makes API pricing work: Stripe, Twilio, GitHub, and every commercial API uses rate limiting to differentiate tiers. The 429 response with a Retry-After header is part of the developer experience — it tells the consumer exactly what happened and when to try again. Rate limiting is the cheapest, highest-impact infrastructure investment you can make — a few hours of work prevents an entire category of outages and attacks.",
       numbers:"Common rate limit tiers for a commercial API: free tier 60–100 req/min (GitHub uses 60/hr unauthenticated), basic tier 1,000 req/min, professional tier 10,000 req/min, enterprise tier 100,000 req/min or custom. Burst allowance: typically 2–5× the sustained rate for a short window (the 'bucket size' in token bucket terms — allows a burst of 500 requests followed by a sustained 100/min). Per-IP limits for anonymous traffic: 1,000 req/min/IP as a floor (prevents basic DDoS and brute force). Per-endpoint limits for expensive operations: /login should have much tighter limits (5–10 attempts/min/IP to prevent credential stuffing) than /list-products (1,000/min). Algorithm comparison: token bucket (best default — allows controlled bursts, simple to implement, O(1) per check, used by AWS, Google Cloud). Sliding window log (most accurate — tracks exact timestamps of every request, but O(N) memory where N = requests in window). Sliding window counter (good compromise — O(1) memory, approximate but >99% accurate, used by Redis-based implementations). GCRA (mathematically equivalent to leaky bucket, O(1), elegant — used by Cloudflare, Shopify). Storage: a Redis-based rate limiter uses ~100 bytes per rate-limited key; 1 million active users × 3 limit tiers = 300MB of Redis memory."
     },
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Strict limits vs Developer experience",left:"Tight limits protect your system aggressively but frustrate legitimate heavy users who hit walls — especially during testing or bulk operations",right:"Generous limits are developer-friendly but leave you more exposed to abuse and unexpected traffic spikes — one bad actor can impact everyone",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Accuracy vs Speed (centralized vs distributed counting)",left:"Centralized counter in Redis: exact global count, every request checks Redis (~0.5ms overhead) — accurate but adds latency and creates a dependency on Redis",right:"Local counters per instance (no coordination): zero latency overhead, no external dependency — but with 10 instances, the effective limit is 10× the configured limit since each instance enforces independently",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Rate limiting at the edge vs at the origin",left:"Edge rate limiting (CDN/gateway layer): blocks abusive traffic before it reaches your servers — saves backend resources, fastest response (the 429 is returned from the nearest PoP)",right:"Origin rate limiting (application layer): more context available for sophisticated limiting (per-user, per-feature, per-tenant-tier) — but abusive traffic still hits your servers before being rejected",pos:0.5}
     ],
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"No 429 Retry-After header — the retry storm",desc:"Client gets a 429 status code with no information about when they can retry. The client retries immediately. Gets another 429. Retries again. You now have a retry storm that's worse than the original traffic. Always include the Retry-After header with the number of seconds the client should wait: 'Retry-After: 30'. Better yet, also include rate limit headers in every response (not just 429s) so clients can self-regulate: X-RateLimit-Limit (total allowed), X-RateLimit-Remaining (left in this window), X-RateLimit-Reset (when the window resets, as Unix timestamp). The IETF draft RFC 'RateLimit Header Fields' standardizes these. Well-designed SDKs (Stripe's, GitHub's) automatically respect these headers and implement exponential backoff."},
       {name:"Rate limiting on the wrong key — the NAT problem",desc:"You rate-limit by IP address. A corporate office with 5,000 employees behind a single NAT gateway appears as one IP. Your limit of 1,000 req/min/IP means only the first 200 employees can use your API simultaneously — the rest get 429s despite being legitimate users. Meanwhile, an attacker with a botnet of 10,000 residential IPs each making 999 req/min sails under the limit. The fix: use IP-based limiting only as a floor for anonymous/unauthenticated traffic (anti-DDoS). For authenticated traffic, always limit by API key, user ID, or organization ID — these are the semantically correct units. For sophisticated protection: combine both — per-IP limit at the edge (stops DDoS) plus per-user limit at the application layer (enforces fair usage and tier pricing)."},
       {name:"Local-only limiting in a distributed system — the 10× problem",desc:"Each of your 10 application instances enforces its own rate limit of 1,000 req/min per user. But since there's no coordination between instances, a user can actually make 10,000 req/min (1,000 on each instance). Your advertised limit is 10× more permissive than documented. Solutions: (1) Shared state in Redis (most common — use Redis INCR with EXPIRE for simple counting, or the Redis Cell module for token bucket). Adds ~0.5ms per rate check but provides accurate global counting. (2) Accept the multiplication factor and document your limit as 'approximately 1,000 req/min' — acceptable if exact enforcement isn't critical. (3) Sticky sessions at the load balancer (route each user to the same instance) — then local counting is accurate, but you lose load balancing flexibility. Most production systems use approach (1) — Redis-based shared counting."},
       {name:"No rate limit on auth/expensive endpoints — the credential stuffing and compute bomb",desc:"Your /login endpoint has no specific rate limit (or shares the generous global limit of 10,000/min). An attacker fires 10,000 credential stuffing attempts per minute, testing stolen username/password pairs from other breaches. At 10,000 bcrypt hash checks per minute, you're consuming significant CPU, potentially slowing down legitimate authentication. Or: your /search endpoint runs expensive full-text queries with no limit. A malicious user automates 1,000 complex search queries per minute, saturating your Elasticsearch cluster. Fix: tier your rate limits by endpoint cost. Auth endpoints: 5–10 attempts/min/IP, 20/min/account. Search: 60/min for free, 600/min for paid. Export/report generation: 5/hour. Static reads (product listing, profile view): generous limits. The more expensive the endpoint (in CPU, DB, or external API cost), the tighter the limit should be."},
       {name:"Rate limiting that doesn't differentiate between read and write",desc:"You set 1,000 req/min globally per API key. A client makes 999 read requests (cheap) and 1 write request. Another client makes 500 write requests. Both hit the same limit, but the second client is consuming 500× more resources. Consider separate rate limits for reads vs writes, or weighted rate limiting where writes consume more 'tokens' than reads (a write costs 5 tokens, a read costs 1 — the 1,000-token-per-minute budget allows 1,000 reads OR 200 writes OR a mix)."},
       {name:"Forgetting to rate limit webhooks and callbacks you receive",desc:"You receive webhooks from a partner (payment processor, shipping provider). They have a bug and send 100,000 webhook deliveries in 1 minute. Your webhook handler dutifully processes each one, overwhelming your database. Rate limit incoming webhooks just like you rate limit outgoing API responses. Queue incoming webhooks (SQS, Redis queue) and process at a sustainable rate, returning 200 immediately to the sender."}
     ],
     examples:[
       {name:"GitHub's tiered API rate limits — the industry reference",desc:"GitHub's rate limiting is transparent and well-documented: 60 req/hr for unauthenticated requests (just IP-based, intentionally very low), 5,000 req/hr for authenticated requests (personal access token or OAuth), 15,000 req/hr for GitHub Apps (enterprise integrations). The search API has a separate, tighter limit (30 req/min authenticated) because search queries are more expensive. Every response includes X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, and X-RateLimit-Reset headers. When rate-limited, the response includes a clear error message, the limit that was hit, and documentation links. GitHub also implements secondary rate limits (abuse detection) that trigger on suspicious patterns even if the primary rate limit isn't exceeded — such as making many requests to a single endpoint in rapid succession. This layered approach (primary rate limits + abuse detection) is the gold standard."},
       {name:"Cloudflare's edge rate limiting — stopping abuse before it reaches you",desc:"Cloudflare enforces rate limiting at the edge PoP closest to the user, before the request reaches your origin server. This means abusive traffic is blocked within 10ms at the Cloudflare PoP — it never consumes your bandwidth, your server CPU, or your database connections. At scale, edge-local limiting is the only viable approach: if you tried to check a centralized Redis counter for every request at 10M RPS across 300 PoPs, the Redis coordination latency would dominate. Cloudflare uses per-PoP local counters with eventual global reconciliation — the limit is approximately correct globally (accurate within ~10%) but exactly correct locally. For most use cases, this approximation is more than sufficient."},
       {name:"Stripe's rate limiting with grace and clarity",desc:"Stripe's rate limits are generous (100 req/sec for most endpoints) but strictly enforced. When a client hits the limit, Stripe returns a 429 with a clear error object: { 'error': { 'type': 'rate_limit_error', 'message': 'Too many requests too quickly. Please retry with exponential backoff.' } }. Stripe's client libraries (stripe-python, stripe-node, stripe-ruby) have built-in automatic retry with exponential backoff and jitter — the SDK handles rate limits transparently without the developer writing any retry logic. This is the developer experience gold standard: generous limits + clear errors + SDKs that handle limits automatically = developers never think about rate limiting."},
       {name:"Twitter's rate limit windows and response headers",desc:"Twitter's API returns rate limit state in every response via headers: x-rate-limit-limit (ceiling for the 15-min window), x-rate-limit-remaining (requests left), x-rate-limit-reset (Unix timestamp when the window resets). This transparency allows client applications to self-regulate: they can check remaining requests and slow down before hitting the wall, rather than hammering until they get a 429. This cooperative approach — the server informs, the client self-regulates — is more efficient than pure enforcement because it prevents the 429 + retry cycle entirely for well-behaved clients."}
     ],
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"Simple IP-based limiting, <10K RPS",rec:"Use your web framework's rate-limiting middleware — it takes 10 minutes to add and prevents the most basic abuse scenarios. At small scale, in-memory counters (stored in the application process) are sufficient. If you have multiple instances, accept approximate limits or use Redis. Token bucket algorithm is the best default (allows bursts, simple to understand). Technology choices: express-rate-limit (Node.js — 5 lines of code to add, in-memory or Redis-backed, supports custom key functions), rack-attack (Ruby on Rails — mature, widely used, supports throttling + blocklisting + safelisting), Flask-Limiter (Python — decorator-based, Redis or in-memory storage), Django Ratelimit (Python — similar). For Redis-backed shared counting: Redis INCR + EXPIRE (simplest approach — increment a counter keyed by client ID + window, set TTL to window duration) or redis-cell module (implements GCRA natively in Redis — more sophisticated, recommended by Cloudflare).",tools:["express-rate-limit","rack-attack","Flask-Limiter","Django Ratelimit","redis-cell"]},
       medium:{range:"Per-user and per-API-key limiting, 10K–100K RPS",rec:"Rate limiting moves to the API gateway layer (Kong, AWS API Gateway, Envoy) so it's enforced consistently across all services without per-service implementation. Use sliding window algorithm for accuracy. Differentiate limits by endpoint: /login = 10/min (very tight, anti-credential-stuffing), /search = 60/min (expensive operation), /list = 1,000/min (cheap reads). Include standard rate limit headers in every response (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset). Configure a DLQ equivalent: when clients are rate-limited, log the events for analysis (who's hitting limits? is it legitimate usage that needs a higher tier, or abuse?). Technology comparison: Kong rate-limiting plugin (built-in, supports local or Redis-backed counters, per-consumer/per-route/global scopes — the quickest path for Kong users). AWS API Gateway throttling (built-in, per-stage and per-method, burst + sustained rate — but limited to account-level quotas). Envoy rate limit service (lyft/ratelimit — a standalone gRPC service that Envoy calls to check rates, backed by Redis — more flexible but requires running a separate service). Redis Cell (implements GCRA in Redis as a native module — the most mathematically elegant rate limiting, O(1) per check, recommended for custom implementations).",tools:["Kong rate-limit plugin","AWS API Gateway throttling","Envoy + lyft/ratelimit","Redis Cell (GCRA)"]},
       large:{range:"Distributed rate limiting across regions, 100K–500K RPS",rec:"At this scale, a centralized Redis counter becomes a bottleneck or a latency concern (every request makes a Redis round-trip). Distributed rate limiting approaches: (1) Redis Cluster for sharded counters (each rate-limit key lives on a specific Redis shard, distributing the load). (2) Token bucket with periodic sync (each instance maintains local tokens, periodically synchronizes with a central store — allows brief over-limit but eliminates per-request Redis calls). (3) Tiered limiting: edge/CDN handles coarse per-IP limits (Cloudflare, CloudFront WAF), gateway handles per-API-key limits (Kong/Envoy + Redis), application handles fine-grained per-feature limits. Differentiated limits by customer tier are essential for monetization: free=100/min, pro=10K/min, enterprise=custom. Include Retry-After headers on all 429 responses. Build rate limit analytics: dashboards showing top rate-limited users, endpoints, and trends — this data drives both capacity planning and tier pricing decisions. Technology comparison: Envoy external rate limit service (lyft/ratelimit — the most widely used distributed rate limiting solution, backed by Redis, supports per-descriptor rate limits with flexible matching rules). Kong + Redis Cluster (built-in distributed support). Custom sliding window on Redis Cluster (if you need very specific behavior). Cloudflare Rate Limiting (edge-based, per-URI pattern, $0.05/10K good requests — excellent for layer-7 DDoS protection).",tools:["Redis Cluster","Envoy + lyft/ratelimit service","Kong + Redis","Cloudflare Rate Limiting"]},
       hyper:{range:"Per-edge rate limiting + global quota, >500K RPS, global traffic",rec:"At hyper scale, you can't check a central store for every request — the latency and throughput of centralized rate limiting is itself a bottleneck. The solution: per-PoP local limiting (fast, no coordination overhead) with asynchronous global quota enforcement (eventual consistency across PoPs). How it works: each PoP maintains local counters and enforces limits locally. In the background (every 1–10 seconds), PoPs report their counts to a global aggregator, which calculates the total and distributes 'budget' back to each PoP proportional to its traffic share. If the global quota is 100K/min and PoP-A handles 30% of traffic, it gets a budget of 30K/min. This is approximately correct (within ~10% of the true global rate) but zero-latency per request. The GCRA (Generic Cell Rate Algorithm) is the mathematically optimal algorithm here — it naturally handles variable-rate traffic, doesn't require synchronized clocks, and is O(1) per check. Shadow mode for new limits: when introducing a new rate limit, run it in 'shadow' mode first — log what would be rate-limited without actually rejecting requests. Analyze the impact (how many requests would be affected? are they legitimate?) before enforcement. This prevents customer-impacting surprises. Technologies: Custom GCRA implementation (Cloudflare published their implementation approach), edge-local counters (stored in edge workers' memory or edge KV), Envoy with custom rate limit service per PoP, and a global coordination layer (Kafka for count aggregation, or a custom control plane).",tools:["Custom GCRA","edge-local counters","Envoy per-PoP","global coordination via Kafka","shadow mode tooling"]}
     },
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:"Any abuse incident (credential stuffing, scraping, DDoS attempt), or your API becomes publicly accessible (mobile app launch, partner integration, public docs) — the moment untrusted clients can reach your API",action:"Move rate limiting from framework middleware to the API gateway layer for centralized enforcement. Implement per-user/API-key rate limiting (not just per-IP). Create tiered limits that match your pricing tiers. Add proper 429 responses with Retry-After headers and rate limit state headers on every response. How to do it: (1) If using Kong: enable the rate-limiting plugin with Redis backend (kong config add plugin rate-limiting --config.second=100 --config.policy=redis). (2) Create rate limit tiers in your gateway config tied to consumer groups (free, pro, enterprise). (3) For auth endpoints specifically, add a separate tighter limit (5–10/min/IP) — this is your primary defense against credential stuffing. (4) Set up monitoring: track 429 response rate, top rate-limited consumers, and rate limit utilization per tier. Alert if >5% of requests are being rate-limited (either limits are too tight or someone is attacking)."},
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:"Rate limiting Redis is becoming a throughput bottleneck (>50K rate checks/sec on a single Redis node), or you're multi-region and cross-region Redis latency is affecting request latency, or you need per-service rate limits (not just per-client)",action:"Distribute rate limiting across Redis Cluster (shard rate-limit keys across nodes). Implement async quota enforcement for cross-region limiting (local enforcement + background global sync). Add per-service rate limits so one service can't overwhelm another (an internal 'billing service' should have a cap on how many requests it sends to the 'notification service'). How to do it: (1) Deploy Redis Cluster with 3+ nodes; rate-limit keys automatically shard across nodes. (2) For multi-region: each region has its own Redis Cluster for local rate limiting; a background process aggregates counts globally every 5–10 seconds and adjusts per-region budgets. (3) Deploy the Envoy external rate limit service (lyft/ratelimit) as a sidecar or central service — it provides a clean gRPC API for rate checking, backed by Redis, with descriptors for flexible matching (rate limit by user + endpoint + method). (4) Build a rate limit analytics dashboard showing: top rate-limited users (are they legitimate?), endpoint distribution (which endpoints hit limits?), and tier utilization (are free tier users consistently at 100%? That's upsell opportunity)."},
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:"Rate limit coordination adds measurable latency to every request (>1ms for the Redis round-trip), or you need global rate limiting across 100+ PoPs, or you need to rate-limit at the edge before traffic reaches your infrastructure",action:"Move to edge-local approximate limiting with background global reconciliation. How to do it: (1) Deploy rate limiting logic at each edge PoP (Cloudflare Workers with KV, Fastly Compute@Edge with local state, or custom Envoy at each PoP). (2) Each PoP enforces limits locally with GCRA — zero external dependencies per request. (3) Every 5–10 seconds, each PoP reports its per-consumer counts to a global aggregation service (via Kafka or a lightweight custom protocol). (4) The global aggregator calculates total consumption per consumer, compares to the global quota, and pushes updated 'budget allocations' back to each PoP (proportional to each PoP's share of that consumer's traffic). (5) Implement shadow mode: new rate limits run in log-only mode for 1 week before enforcement — analyze the impact, adjust thresholds, then enable enforcement. (6) Build an anomaly detection layer on top of rate limit data: ML-based detection of unusual traffic patterns (sudden 10× spike from a single consumer, geographic distribution change) that trigger dynamic tighter limits."}
     ],
     children:[]}
  ]
};
